+{"id":"bd-u2cl8","title":"Context Window Heat Map Visualization","description":"## Overview

Visual representation of token usage over an agent's session—where tokens went (tool calls, code blocks, reasoning, system prompts). Interactive timeline helps users understand consumption patterns and optimize workflows.

## Background & Justification

The context-health.service.ts tracks context utilization but the data is opaque. Users see "80% context used" but not:
- Where those tokens went (which tool calls were expensive?)
- When context pressure peaked (what operation caused it?)
- How to optimize (which patterns are wasteful?)

Visualization helps:
- Identify token-heavy operations
- Optimize prompts and workflows
- Understand context pressure points
- Debug "why did the context fill up so fast?"

## Key Components

### 1. Token Attribution Tracking

Track token usage by category at each turn:

```typescript
interface TokenAttribution {
  timestamp: Date;
  turn: number;
  category: 'system' | 'user' | 'assistant' | 'tool_call' | 'tool_result' | 
            'code_block' | 'reasoning' | 'context_summary';
  tokens: number;
  description?: string; // e.g., "Read file X (2.5KB)", "Grep search"

  metadata?: {
    toolName?: string;
    filePath?: string;
    resultSize?: number;
    isCached?: boolean;
  };
}

interface ContextSnapshot {
  timestamp: Date;
  turn: number;
  totalTokens: number;
  contextLimit: number;
  utilization: number; // 0-1
  attributions: TokenAttribution[];
}
```

### 2. Heat Map Data Model

```typescript
interface ContextHeatMap {
  agentId: string;
  sessionId: string;
  timeRange: { start: Date; end: Date };
  buckets: HeatMapBucket[];
  totalTokens: number;
  contextLimit: number;
  peakUtilization: number;
  peakTimestamp: Date;
}

interface HeatMapBucket {
  timestamp: Date;
  turn: number;
  duration: number; // seconds
  attributions: {
    [category: string]: number; // tokens per category
  };
  cumulativeTokens: number;
  utilization: number; // 0-1
  isWarning: boolean; // > 80%
  isCritical: boolean; // > 95%
}
```

### 3. Visualization Components

**Heat Map Chart:**
- X-axis: Time (session duration) or Turn number
- Y-axis: Token categories stacked
- Color intensity: Token density (darker = more tokens)
- Hover: Detailed tooltip with breakdown
- Click: Expand to see individual turns

**Category Breakdown:**
- Donut chart of token distribution by category
- Clickable segments to filter timeline
- Legend with totals and percentages

**Utilization Line:**
- Overlay line showing cumulative utilization
- Warning threshold line (80%)
- Critical threshold line (95%)
- Event markers for rotations/summaries

**Timeline Markers:**
- Context rotation events (red vertical line)
- Checkpoint saves (blue marker)
- Tool call boundaries
- Error events

### 4. Interactive Features

**Zoom Controls:**
- Zoom in/out on time range
- Pan across session
- Jump to events (rotation, peak, errors)
- Fit to screen

**Category Filters:**
- Toggle categories on/off
- Compare before/after filtering
- Highlight specific category

**Turn Navigation:**
- Click to jump to specific turn
- Arrow keys to step through
- Link to replay if available

**Analysis Panel:**
- Top 5 most expensive operations
- Suggested optimizations
- Comparison with similar sessions

### 5. Export Features

- PNG/SVG of heat map visualization
- CSV of raw attribution data
- JSON for programmatic analysis

## API Endpoints

- `GET /api/agents/:id/context-heatmap` - Heat map data for session
- `GET /api/agents/:id/context-attributions` - Raw attribution list
- `GET /api/agents/:id/context-summary` - Category totals and stats
- `GET /api/agents/:id/context-history` - Historical comparison
- WebSocket: `agent:{id}:context` - Real-time attribution updates

## Database Schema

```sql
CREATE TABLE context_attributions (
  id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  agent_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  session_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  turn INTEGER NOT NULL,
  timestamp TEXT NOT NULL,
  category TEXT NOT NULL,
  tokens INTEGER NOT NULL,
  description TEXT,
  metadata TEXT, -- JSON
  FOREIGN KEY (agent_id) REFERENCES agents(id)
);

CREATE INDEX idx_attributions_session ON context_attributions(session_id, turn);
CREATE INDEX idx_attributions_agent_time ON context_attributions(agent_id, timestamp DESC);

CREATE TABLE context_snapshots (
  id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  agent_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  session_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  turn INTEGER NOT NULL,
  timestamp TEXT NOT NULL,
  total_tokens INTEGER NOT NULL,
  context_limit INTEGER NOT NULL,
  utilization REAL NOT NULL,
  is_warning INTEGER DEFAULT 0,
  is_critical INTEGER DEFAULT 0,
  FOREIGN KEY (agent_id) REFERENCES agents(id)
);

CREATE INDEX idx_snapshots_session ON context_snapshots(session_id, turn);
```

